
Adventure In Graphics
George Miller

     ' "This place is really nowhere!" This mountain exists inside
a computer,....' So the text under an amazingly realistic picture
of a rugged mountain landscape proclaims in ads from IBM. Of course,
the ads don't state that the image was developed on a high-priced
graphics work station, and can't even be contemplated on the
4 color IBM PC.
  
     Here's a simple but fascinating program, written in GFA BASIC,
taking you on a voyage of discovery through the fascinating world
of fractuals inside your Atari ST.
      
     Switch to Low resolution before running, then select a number
between 0 and 5, including fractions.  Zero represents sea level, 
and your screen will eventually show simply a static sea. Use values
less than one to represent marshy swamplands. Five is the range for
an extremely rugged mountainscape.

     After the image has been created, you'll have the option of
Saving it in .NEO format, viewing the picture, or creating a new
world.

     The idea for this program, and algorythm were obtained from
A.K. Dewdney's 'Computer Recreations' column in Scientific American.
 
     
